David Goodwin wrote:

&gt;Rebecca,
&gt;
&gt;Thanks for reporting the problems.  The way I added the MATLAB files to 
&gt;the SetupCantera project (drap and drop) inadvertently brought in the 
&gt;CVS files.  I though I had removed them all, but I guess I missed some. 
&gt;  I&#39;ll delete them.
&gt;
&gt;The equilibrium error is curious.  I&#39;ll look into why that happens, and 
&gt;see if I can reproduce it on a Mac or linux.
&gt;
&gt;Dave
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;On Dec 15, 2004, at 12:45 PM, R A Hunt wrote:
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;Fantastic.  Thank you so much!
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;  I tested this on a XP machine without Fortran using VStudio .Net and
&gt;&gt;was able to run the matlab and python example scripts.  So far I have
&gt;&gt;only tested the zipped source code, and not tested the procedure with
&gt;&gt;code checked out of CVS.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;I encountered two problems, which I will document here and describe my
&gt;&gt;quick fixes (better solutions are welcomed.)
&gt;&gt;1. PROBLEM: The first problem occurred at the step of building
&gt;&gt;setup_cantera I get the following output
&gt;&gt;----------------snip -------------------
&gt;&gt;------ Starting pre-build validation for project &#39;SetupCantera&#39; ------
&gt;&gt;ERROR: Unable to find source file
&gt;&gt;&#39;cantera-1.5.5&#92;Cantera&#92;matlab&#92;cantera&#92;@Kinetics&#92;private&#92;CVS&#92;Root&#39; for
&gt;&gt;file &#39;Root&#39;, located in
&gt;&gt;&#39;[TARGETDIR]&#92;MATLAB&#92;toolbox&#92;cantera&#92;@Kinetics&#92;private&#92;CVS&#39;, the file 
&gt;&gt;may
&gt;&gt;be absent or locked.
&gt;&gt;ERROR: Unable to find source file
&gt;&gt;&#39;cantera-1.5.5&#92;Cantera&#92;matlab&#92;cantera&#92;@Kinetics&#92;private&#92;CVS&#92;Repository&#39;
&gt;&gt;for file &#39;Repository&#39;, located in
&gt;&gt;&#39;[TARGETDIR]&#92;MATLAB&#92;toolbox&#92;cantera&#92;@Kinetics&#92;private&#92;CVS&#39;, the file 
&gt;&gt;may
&gt;&gt;be absent or locked.
&gt;&gt;ERROR: Unable to find source file
&gt;&gt;&#39;cantera-1.5.5&#92;Cantera&#92;matlab&#92;cantera&#92;@Kinetics&#92;private&#92;CVS&#92;Entries&#39; 
&gt;&gt;for
&gt;&gt;file &#39;Entries&#39;, located in
&gt;&gt;&#39;[TARGETDIR]&#92;MATLAB&#92;toolbox&#92;cantera&#92;@Kinetics&#92;private&#92;CVS&#39;, the file 
&gt;&gt;may
&gt;&gt;be absent or locked.
&gt;&gt;------ Pre-build validation for project &#39;SetupCantera&#39; completed ------
&gt;&gt;------ Build started: Project: SetupCantera, Configuration: Release 
&gt;&gt;------
&gt;&gt;------------------------------------ end snip 
&gt;&gt;---------------------------
&gt;&gt;SOLUTION:  My solution was to edit SetupCantera.vdproj in a text 
&gt;&gt;editor,
&gt;&gt;removing all sections referring to the CVS directories by hand.  I&#39;m 
&gt;&gt;not
&gt;&gt;very familiar with VStudio .NEt yet, so if there is a better way to 
&gt;&gt;edit
&gt;&gt;this file,  let me know.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;2.  PROBLEM: The second small error occurs when running the script
&gt;&gt;run_examples.m in matlab.  Everything seems to be going fin until
&gt;&gt;PRANDTL2 dies with something like:
&gt;&gt;************************************************
&gt;&gt;                Cantera Error!
&gt;&gt;************************************************
&gt;&gt;Procedure: equilibrate
&gt;&gt;Error:   Jacobian is singular.
&gt;&gt;Try adding more species, changing the elemental composition slightly,
&gt;&gt;or removing unused elements.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;SOLUTION:  This is  *not* an indication of a bad build.  This only
&gt;&gt;happens when PRANDTL2 is run with a variable directly after PRANDTL1,
&gt;&gt;without resetting the variable g.  Insert something like &quot;g=0;&quot; into
&gt;&gt;line 26 of run_examples.m and it will run beautifully.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;David Goodwin wrote:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;I have just changed the Cantera version number to 1.5.5, and posted a
&gt;&gt;&gt;Windows source distribution at the sourceforge site
&gt;&gt;&gt;(cantera-1.5.5-src.zip).
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;The big news: Cantera can now be completely built  from within Visual
&gt;&gt;&gt;Studio .NET, including the Python and MATLAB interfaces.  You can also
&gt;&gt;&gt;create your own binary installer programs (.msi files) and distribute
&gt;&gt;&gt;them to install Cantera (+ your own application code) on machines that
&gt;&gt;&gt;do not have Visual Studio.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;Now there is no need to have cygwin (but personally I would install it
&gt;&gt;&gt;anyway), or to do anything from a command line, or to have Fortran.  I
&gt;&gt;&gt;think virtually all Windows installation problems should be gone now.
&gt;&gt;&gt;(Also, the Python location is no longer hard-wired to C:&#92;PYTHON23.)
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;The procedure is described step-by-step in a Powerpoint presentation I
&gt;&gt;&gt;have also posted at the Sourceforge site under &quot;Cantera Documentation&quot;
&gt;&gt;&gt;- see file cantera-vc7.ppt.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;Other than that, you may notice a new class &quot;Mixture&quot; in Python, and a
&gt;&gt;&gt;couple of new classes (MultiPhase and MultiPhaseEquil) in C++. These
&gt;&gt;&gt;implement multi-phase mixtures and a new multi-phase equilibrium
&gt;&gt;&gt;solver.  It is fully functional in Python and C++ now (MATLAB soon),
&gt;&gt;&gt;but is not documented, so its official introduction will be in Cantera
&gt;&gt;&gt;1.6 which will be out in January.  Cantera 1.6 will contain also some
&gt;&gt;&gt;new phase models, and some improved support for non-ideal phases.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;Windows people in particular - if you have Visual C++ .NET, please try
&gt;&gt;&gt;out the new build procedure, and report any problems.
